\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f0\fs22\lang9 Creating List Groups with Bootstrap\par
The list groups are very useful and flexible component for displaying lists of elements in a beautiful manner. In most basic form a list group is simply an unordered list with the class .list-group whereas, the list items having the class .list-group-item.\par
\par
<!DOCTYPE html>\par
<html lang="en">\par
<head>\par
<meta charset="utf-8">\par
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">\par
<title>Bootstrap List Group</title>\par
<link href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/bootstrap@5.0.2/dist/css/bootstrap.min.css" rel="stylesheet">\par
<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/bootstrap@5.0.2/dist/js/bootstrap.bundle.min.js"></script>\par
</head>\par
<body>\par
<div class="m-4">\par
    <ul class="list-group w-50">\par
        <li class="list-group-item">Pictures</li>\par
        <li class="list-group-item">Documents</li>\par
        <li class="list-group-item">Music</li>\par
        <li class="list-group-item">Videos</li>\par
    </ul>\par
</div>\par
</body>\par
</html>\par
\par
Tip: List groups are 100% wide by default. To set their width explicitly you can either use the Bootstrap's width utility classes (e.g. w-25, w-50, etc.) or place them inside grid columns.\par
\par
Indicate Disabled and Active Items\par
You can simply add the class .active to a .list-group-item to indicate the current active selection. Similarly, you can add .disabled to a .list-group-item to make it look like disabled.\par
\par
ExampleTry this code \'bb\par
<ul class="list-group w-50">\par
    <li class="list-group-item active">Pictures</li>\par
    <li class="list-group-item">Documents</li>        \par
    <li class="list-group-item">Music</li>\par
    <li class="list-group-item disabled">Videos</li>\par
</ul>\par
